Radiation is essentially atoms being kicked off their covalent bonds from matter that is unstable and cannot hold the number of atomic orbits it has. radiation is basically these free flying atoms. When they collide with molecules they can break bonds like hydrogen to cause water to evaporate or cause fats to liquify. When they hit an organic cell they can pepper it like bullets, if they hit specific DNA strains they can cause the cell to grow without any restraints making what we know as a form of cancer or tumors.

That's the D+ grade definition of it.

I'm gonna be serious. HFY has always been a thing in sci-fi, back before the Internet. It's more popular some years than others. Gordon R. Dickson made a career out of writing HFY stories just after the Second World War. John Ringo is writing HFY stories right now, with the Legacy of the Aldenata series. Christopher Anvil did it, lots of Poul Anderson's work falls into this category. See also, Larry Niven. See also, Jerry Pournelle. I could go on and on.

I can see the attraction of it in small doses, especially ever since 1960s "New Wave" sci-fi created the sub-genre of "Humanity Sucks and should get Cucked and Exterminated and We'll Deserve It" stories, which are always tiresome. See also, Peter Watts. HFY, if the author can restrain himself from going completely out of his mind and masturbating the words onto the page instead of typing, can be fun. In small doses. If the author puts more thought into it than the NoP guy.
